---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import OpportunityCard from '@/components/OpportunityCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="PDP Competitor Analysis — June 2026">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">PDP Competitor Analysis</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Product Detail Page &mdash; Analysed 8 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Three competitor PDPs were reviewed against Myprotein's Impact Whey Protein page:
      The Protein Works (Whey Protein 360), Optimum Nutrition (Gold Standard 100% Whey),
      and Healf (Sprout Living Epic Protein). Seven opportunities were identified across
      the three — spanning upsell architecture, review intelligence, subscription framing,
      and in-page personalisation. None are currently present on Myprotein's Impact Whey PDP.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── The Protein Works ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">The Protein Works</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">theproteinworks.com &mdash; Whey Protein 360 BLACK Innovation</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="In-page product tier comparison table"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Desktop"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="tpw-tier-comparison-table"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the main product content, TPW includes a "Worth the upgrade?" section presenting a
        structured side-by-side table comparing their three whey tiers (BLACK, GOLD, PLATINUM)
        across ~10 nutritional attributes: price per serving, protein per serving, protein sources,
        calories, vitamins &amp; minerals, approved health benefits, flavour count, digestive enzymes,
        and GLP-1 compatibility. Each column is framed with a purchase-intent label ("Best Price",
        "Best Value", "Best Rated") and uses check/cross marks for boolean attributes. Links from
        the table go directly to each tier's product page.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-tier-comparison-detail.png" alt="TPW in-page product tier comparison table showing BLACK, GOLD and PLATINUM tiers side by side" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A user on an entry-level product page is often mid-decision — they know they want whey
        but haven't committed to a tier. Surfacing the upgrade comparison on the same page captures
        that indecision in favour of a higher-value product without requiring navigation elsewhere.
        The framing ("Best Price" vs "Best Value") doesn't make the entry tier feel inferior — it
        makes the middle tier feel obviously worth the small price increase. This is a well-established
        CRO pattern for increasing average order value.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein sells Impact Whey, Impact Whey Advanced, and THE Whey as a de facto tier stack
        but the PDP makes no attempt to surface this. A user on Impact Whey has no in-page prompt
        to consider Impact Whey Advanced without navigating away. A compact "Compare the range"
        module — even a 2-column card comparison — could intercept undecided shoppers. The labelling
        approach ("Best Value", "Most Popular") is worth borrowing directly.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Per-serving price on each size option"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="tpw-per-serving-price"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW's size selector displays the price-per-serving directly beneath each size chip:
        20 shakes (600g) at £0.55 each, 40 shakes at £0.50 each, 80 shakes at £0.43 each,
        160 shakes at £0.40 each. The cost-per-serving is always visible — no interaction required.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-size-selector-detail.png" alt="TPW size selector showing per-serving price beneath each size option" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A larger bag is a higher upfront price. Showing cost-per-serving reframes the decision:
        the larger purchase becomes cheaper per use, not just a bigger spend. This framing reduces
        the psychological friction of committing to a larger size and nudges users toward higher-value
        orders. It also eliminates the mental arithmetic a user would otherwise have to do themselves.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows the total price per size option but does not display price-per-serving on
        the size chips. Adding cost-per-serving beneath each size option on Impact Whey would make
        the value case for larger sizes immediately legible — particularly for a product sold in
        sizes ranging from 500g to 5kg, where the per-serve savings on larger bags are significant.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Rating distribution bars with percentage breakdown"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust"
      opportunityId="tpw-rating-breakdown-bars"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW's reviews section shows the full star-by-star percentage distribution alongside the
        aggregate score: 5★ 40%, 4★ 4%, 3★ 8%, 2★ 11%, 1★ 37%. Each tier has a proportional
        horizontal bar and explicit percentage. The distribution is shown unfiltered — even when
        the split is unflattering.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-reviews-breakdown-detail.png" alt="TPW rating distribution showing percentage bars per star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Showing the full distribution is paradoxically a trust signal. Users who see only an
        aggregate score are left to wonder whether it reflects genuine spread. A visible distribution
        lets customers self-qualify — a user who reads 1-star reviews to understand failure modes
        is more informed and less likely to return. Hiding the distribution invites suspicion;
        showing it honestly reduces it.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows an aggregate rating and total count but no star-by-star breakdown on the PDP.
        With 210,000+ reviews, Myprotein has far more data to make this credible and useful. A
        distribution bar chart in the reviews section — showing the likely dominant 4- and 5-star
        clusters on Impact Whey — would add a transparency signal without undermining confidence.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Optimum Nutrition ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Optimum Nutrition</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">optimumnutrition.com &mdash; Gold Standard 100% Whey Protein Powder</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Review attribute highlights beside the star rating"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,conversion"
      opportunityId="on-review-attribute-highlights"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Directly below ON's star rating and review count, a short inline callout reads:
        <strong>"Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money."</strong>
        Each attribute is a clickable link that jumps to the reviews section filtered to reviews
        mentioning that dimension. The callout appears above the product bullets and the
        add-to-cart area — it is the first thing a user reads after the aggregate score.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-atf-detail.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition PDP showing 'Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money' directly below the star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A star rating tells a user how well-liked a product is. An attribute summary tells them
        <em>why</em>. For a shopper comparing two proteins with similar ratings, "Taste and Mixability"
        called out explicitly is a significantly stronger signal than "4.4 stars". It collapses
        the work of reading dozens of reviews into a three-word reassurance, and the clickable
        links give curious users a direct path to filtered evidence.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score and total count but does not break reviews
        down by attribute near the rating. With 210,000+ reviews on Impact Whey, the data to surface
        attribute-level highlights clearly exists. Even a static, editorially curated version —
        "Customers rate this highly for taste variety and value per serving" — near the star rating
        would provide this signal. A dynamic version powered by review tagging would be the stronger
        long-term implementation.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="AI-generated review summary with topic filter chips"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,content"
      opportunityId="on-ai-review-summary"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        At the top of ON's reviews section, before any individual review, an AI-synthesised paragraph
        summarises what customers say: <em>"Customers praise its great taste, easy mixing, and high
        value, making it a top choice for serious athletes."</em> Below the search and sort controls
        sits a row of topic filter chips — "size", "ingredients", "results", "absorption", "quality",
        "weight", "smell", "taste" — each filtering the review list to reviews mentioning that topic.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-reviews-section.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition reviews section showing AI summary paragraph and topic filter chips" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        No one reads 1,725 reviews. An AI synthesis gives users the substance of the community's
        verdict in ten seconds. For high-review-count products, the reviews section risks becoming
        noise rather than signal — the summary resolves this. The topic chips extend the utility:
        a user who cares specifically about mixability can filter directly rather than hunting through
        pages. Together they turn the reviews section from a scrollable wall of text into a
        structured, navigable knowledge base.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey has 210,000+ reviews — a dataset that makes ON's 1,725 look nascent.
        Yet the reviews section is a standard paginated list with star and sort filters only — no
        synthesis, no topic navigation, no AI summary. A product with this review volume is exactly
        where an AI summary would be most useful and most credible. Even a static editorial summary
        updated quarterly would be a meaningful step. Topic chips mapped to common themes — flavour,
        mixability, value, results — would be relatively low effort against an existing tagged
        review corpus.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Healf ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Healf</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">healf.com &mdash; Sprout Living Epic Protein (Vanilla Lucuma)</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Goal-based use-case chips above the add-to-cart"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="personalisation,conversion"
      opportunityId="healf-goal-chips"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Immediately below the product title and star rating, Healf asks: "What's your focus with
        [product name]?" and presents four selectable chips: "Muscle building", "Recovery",
        "Weight management", "Something else". Selecting a chip is paired with an "Assess
        suitability" entry point (a tab alongside "Product description") that helps users determine
        whether the product fits their specific goal. Both elements appear above the price and
        add-to-cart section.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-subscribe-cta-detail.png" alt="Healf PDP showing goal chips (Muscle building, Recovery, Weight management) and Assess suitability tab above the add-to-cart" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Protein powder is bought for different reasons by different people. A user targeting
        muscle building needs to know about protein-per-serving and amino acid profile; a recovery
        buyer cares about EAAs and digestibility. A goal chip doesn't just personalise the
        experience — it signals that the brand understands why the user is here, which reduces
        purchase hesitation. The suitability assessment adds a layer of confidence: the user
        is being actively helped to make the right decision rather than left to judge alone.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey PDP makes no attempt to qualify the user's goal or surface
        goal-specific content. For a product used across a wide range of goals — muscle gain,
        weight loss, general health, sports recovery — a simple goal chip selector could unlock
        context-relevant content: the relevant benefit bullets, a matched FAQ, or a
        "this product is a good fit for you" confirmation signal. Even a static version (chips
        that scroll to a relevant section) would add meaningful reassurance before the add-to-cart.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Subscribe & save as primary CTA with inline benefit callouts"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="healf-subscribe-primary-cta"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        On Healf's PDP, the subscription option is presented as the dominant choice — it is the
        first, darker button in the add-to-cart area, labelled "Subscribe &amp; save 10%", with
        the discounted price (£32.84) alongside the crossed-out full price (£41.99). Two inline
        benefit lines sit beneath it: "✓ Free delivery on subscriptions" and "✓ Free sample each
        month". A sticky bar persists at the bottom of the screen throughout the page scroll,
        showing the same subscription framing and price.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-lower-desktop.png" alt="Healf sticky ATC bar showing Subscribe & save 10% as primary CTA with discounted price" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Defaulting to subscription — rather than treating it as an optional upgrade — changes
        the conversion dynamic. The user's path of least resistance is now the recurring order,
        not the one-time purchase. Showing the specific benefits inline (free delivery, free
        sample) makes the value exchange concrete at the moment of decision, rather than requiring
        the user to hunt for subscription terms. The sticky bar ensures this framing is always
        present regardless of where the user is on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein has a Subscribe &amp; Save option on PDPs but it is presented as a secondary
        choice alongside the standard one-time purchase. Inverting the hierarchy — making
        Subscribe the primary/pre-selected option and adding two or three specific benefit
        callouts inline ("Free delivery · Cancel anytime · Save X%") — would increase subscription
        conversion without requiring the user to seek out the option. This is a framing change
        rather than a feature build.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Where MP Leads ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Areas Where Myprotein Already Leads</h2>
    <p>
      Myprotein's review volume (210,000+ on Impact Whey alone) is a trust advantage that none
      of these three competitors come close to matching — ON has ~1,725, TPW has 135, and Healf's
      listed product has 27. Myprotein's flavour range (50+ for Impact Whey) far exceeds all three.
      The Trustpilot aggregate score is already surfaced on the Myprotein PDP, as it is on TPW's
      and ON's — this is a draw, not a gap. Myprotein's structured content tabs (nutrition,
      ingredients, key benefits, reviews) give users more ways to explore detail without navigating
      away than any of the three competitor pages reviewed. The product image gallery on Myprotein's
      PDP is also stronger than ON's sparse presentation, and the add-to-bag area is clean and clear.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Screenshots ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="screenshots-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Page Screenshots</h2>

    <h3 class="screenshot-competitor">The Protein Works</h3>
    <div class="screenshot-grid">
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">The Protein Works — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-full-desktop.png" alt="The Protein Works Whey Protein 360 PDP desktop" />
      </div>
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Myprotein — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png" alt="Myprotein Impact Whey Protein PDP desktop" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="screenshot-competitor">Optimum Nutrition</h3>
    <div class="screenshot-grid">
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Optimum Nutrition — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-full-desktop.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition Gold Standard Whey PDP desktop" />
      </div>
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Myprotein — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png" alt="Myprotein Impact Whey Protein PDP desktop" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="screenshot-competitor">Healf</h3>
    <div class="screenshot-grid">
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Healf — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-full-desktop.png" alt="Healf Sprout Living Epic Protein PDP desktop" />
      </div>
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Myprotein — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png" alt="Myprotein Impact Whey Protein PDP desktop" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }

  .competitor-section { margin-bottom: 56px; }

  .competitor-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    padding-bottom: 12px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1);
  }

  .competitor-name {
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .competitor-url {
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    opacity: 0.45;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }

  .screenshots-section { margin-top: 48px; }
  .screenshot-competitor { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin: 28px 0 12px; opacity: 0.6; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
  .screenshot-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 32px; }
  .screenshot-col img { width: 100%; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08); display: block; margin-top: 8px; }
  .screenshot-label { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.55; margin: 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
</style>
